						<summary>

						<p>On a slab set up outside the northern <hi rend="italic">prākāra</hi> wall of the Chennakēśava svāmi temple.</p>						

						<p>EṞIKAL MUTTURĀJU.</p>						

						<p>6th century A.D.</p>						

						<p>This undated inscription can be assigned to the 6th century A.D. on the basis of palaeography and internal evidences.</p>						

						<p>Records the gift of wild corn land <hi rend="italic">(nivari)</hi> land measuring twenty four <hi rend="italic">maṟuturu (iruvadiyādi-nāku)</hi> as pannasa to a <hi rend="italic">brāhmin</hi> residing in a territorial division koṭṭambu by Kuṇḍikāḷḷu (an officer ?) with the permission of Eṟrikal Mutturāju who was ruling the earth. The witnesses to the deed are Dujayarājulu, Mutturājulu, Navapriyarājulu and Pallava Dukarājulu.</p>						

						<p>(Pub. <hi rend="italic">Epigraphia Indica.</hi> Vol. XXVII, pp 225 ff. and pl.)</p>						

						</summary>
